ce:section.ce:para:
To examine the electrochemical performance of the Co3O4-based nanocomposites as a battery-type electrode for HSCs, CV measurements were done in a three-electrode system in 2M KOH from 0 to 0.6 V. Fig.5
                     a exhibits the CV plots of pristine Co3O4 ranging from 5 to 50mV/s. Interestingly, the CV curves of the CQDs/Co3O4 hierarchical structures exhibit different characteristics from pristine Co3O4 nanoplates. The main reason is: (1) The product from Co2+ to Co3+, simultaneously suffers oxidation reaction of Co3+→Co4+; (2) The electrochemical redox potentials of the Co2+/Co3+ reaction, as well as the conversion between Co3+ and Co4+, are so close that the redox peaks are readily overlapped [25]. This may be due to the strong chemical interactions between Co3O4 and CQDs [26]. Moreover, with a 40-fold increase of the scan rate, the redox peaks only shift slightly, implying a fast electron and ion transport rates and good electrochemical reversibility (Fig.5c, e). It is noted that the integrated areas of the CV curves for the CQDs/Co3O4 composite are apparently larger than that of pristine Co3O4, showing a higher special capacity. We also explored the effect of scan rates on the anodic peak currents of the CQDs/Co3O4. The anodic current (Ip
                     ) increases linearly with the increase of square root of the scan rate (v1/2
                     ) (the inset in Fig.5e), meaning the redox reaction of the hybrid electrode is a diffusion-limited reaction in KOH solution [27–29]. The CV curves (Figs. S4, S5) of the other MxOy and the CQDs/MxOy electrodes also reveal similar phenomena. What’s more, as the scan rate increased, the peak currents were also boosted, indicating the 3D hierarchical nanocomposites have a larger areal capacity. Galvanostatic charge-discharge voltage profiles of Co3O4 and CQDs/Co3O4 were performed range of 1–100Ag−1in a voltage from 0 to 0.53V. The nonlinear charge-discharge profile (Fig.5b, d, f) also confirms the redox behaviour of the electrode materials, which is in agreement with the CV results, further revealing battery-like characteristics of the electrodes. In addition, Galvanostatic charge-discharge voltage profiles of the other MxOy and the CQDs/MxOy electrodes also show similar phenomena (Figs. S4, S5).
